external_knowledge:
- "bustling hubs" refers to districts with above-average population density;
- "thicker than the norm" signifies that the average population density is greater than the overall average;
- "closely observed by researchers over the past decade" implies researchers accessed data for these districts between 2010 and 2020.

- "bustling city seas" refers to districts with high population density;
- "top five districts" refers to the top 5 entries returned by the query;
- "waves of data sorted by district ID and year" refers to the ORDER BY clause in the query;
- "above the average" refers to districts whose population density is higher than the average population density across all districts.

sql:
SELECT district_id, COUNT(id) AS num_forecast_accesses
FROM FORECAST_ACCESS
GROUP BY district_id;

SELECT user_name 
FROM users 
WHERE user_id NOT IN (
  SELECT DISTINCT user_id 
  FROM report_access
);

SELECT district_id, forecast_population, forecast_male, forecast_female
FROM FORECAST_DATA
WHERE year = 2010;

SELECT district_name
FROM districts
WHERE population_density > (
    SELECT AVG(population_density)
    FROM districts
);
